, Meath, Leinster, Ireland":"Ireland, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Crickstown, Dunshaughlin, County Meath, Ireland":"Crickstown, Dunshaughlin, County Meath, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rochford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Niall.","English: variant of   Ratchford  .","Irish: of Norman origin, probably brought to Ireland by the Normans after 1171, when Henry II acquired Dublin. However, it is not known if it was an English name (see   Ratchford  ), or a Norman equivalent of the French name   Rochefort  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rockford","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Rochford   or   Ratchford  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Rachford","meanings":["English:","variant of   Rochford  .","variant of<b>Rackford</b>, a habitational name from Rackenford in Devon,recorded in Domesday Book as <i>Racheneforda</i>, which Millsinterprets as ‘ford suitable for riding, by a stretch of river’."]},{"name":"Ratchford","meanings":["habitational name from Rochford (Worcestershire), from Old English <i>ræcc</i> ‘hunting dog’ (genitive <i>ræcces</i>) + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’.","habitational name from Rochford (Essex). Early forms of the name ending in <i>Ro-</i> suggest that the placename derives from Old English <i>hrōc</i> ‘rook’ or the Old English personal name <i>Hrōc(a)</i> + Old English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, but the 13th century forms in <i>Ra-</i> and <i>Re-</i> suggest that the first element is Old English <i>ræcc</i> ‘hunting dog’.","English:"]},{"name":"Rotchford","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Caitlin.","Irish and English: variant of   Rochford  ."]}]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Eleanor Rochford was born about 1370, in County Kildare, Ireland, her father, Sir Nicholas Rochford, Knight, was 28 and her mother, Mrs. Sir Nicholas Rockford Knight, was 24. She married Sir Christopher de Berneval I, Knight in 1385, in Ireland. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died after 1398, in Ireland."},"et":{"about 1370–after 1398":"umbes 1370–pärast 1398","1370–1398":"1370–1398","1370–1400":"1370–1400","1440–1452":"1440–1452","1385–Male":"1385–Surnud","1390–1446":"1390–1446","1398–1433":"1398–1433","1344–Male":"1344–Surnud","1348–Female":"1348–Surnud","about 1370":"umbes 1370","1385":"1385","1440":"1440","1370":"1370","1390":"1390","1348":"1348","1446":"1446","1433":"1433","1400":"1400","1344":"1344","1398":"1398","1452":"1452","after 1385":"pärast 1385","after 1398":"pärast 1398","Irel